Written September 4, 2019
Zach95014
Cupertino, CA49 contributions
3
Sapphire Cruise - Great, not Amazing
Jul 2019 ‚Ä¢ Couples
Halong Bay Information:
We took a short, 2 day, 1 night cruise through the bay. Unfortunately, when we came in July, it was incredibly overcast and foggy/cloudy during the first day.
Yes, there is trash in the water, but it's not as much as people are pointing out here. This is not an excuse to not be good stewards of the earth and to clean up and be conscious of the nature reserve, especially as a UNESCO site, but it definitely wasn't as bad as I thought it was going to be.
The cruise that we went on also didn't have that many boats around us - we only had a handful of other cruise ships that we could see, so it didn't feel like we were being overcrowded or too touristy in the area that we went to, which was nice.
The second day, early in the morning when it became more clear, the bay was much more stunning and spectacular than the first. Definitely, a clear day makes the bay an incredible site to see, and definitely a must-do if you're able to get there.
Swimming in the water was nice - the water is incredibly warm, which I would think poses a problem to the wildlife there, but it wasn't as gross as other reviewers make it out to be. It isn't as clear as a tropical island, but what do you expect? The size of the bay is bigger than Singapore, and with so much tourism + industrial boats coming through, it's not going to be a pristine lake.
Kayaking was nice - you don't need too long, maybe a couple of hours, to fully grasp the feeling of the place. Unless there are specific islands to see or places to go, seeing 2 or 3 of the islands felt like enough.
Cruise Tour Information:
We booked a cruise tour with Halong Bay Cruise Hunters, who seemed to arrange the tour through VietnamOpenTour. We were picked up from our hotel in Hanoi for our (2 people) 2 day, 1 night cruise.
It took about 2 hours to get from Hanoi to the harbor, where we transferred our stuff to a smaller boat. The smaller boat took us to our ship, the Sapphire Cruise. It was a 3-star cruise, with a clean room with working AC and a generously sized bathroom. We also received a small balcony to look out, which was nice.
We arrived on the boat around 1 PM, where we were served lunch. We went out kayaking for an hour and swimming in the bay for an hour, both of which were nice. Kayaking for an hour seemed to be OK - once you've seen one or two of the islands, that's really enough, unless you're specifically looking for something else. Swimming for an hour was also about enough - we were able to jump off the boat a few times, get some great pictures, and enjoy the water, which was quite warmer than the California ocean waters I'm used to.
The dinner was fantastic, and we were able to go squid fishing (which was just fishing with a bamboo rod and a bare lure) off the side. Pro Tip: turn off the lights to have a better chance of catching squid.
The next morning, we got an early start (activity start at 7:30 AM) where we sat in a boat while some locals rowed the boat through a cave and around a small cove.
We returned back to the main cruise ship for some brunch, and then headed back to the harbor.
The cruise was quick, but felt like just enough time. I think that if we had done one more day, we would've experienced more of the same.
Written July 17, 2019
Lisa.strobel
Cologne, Germany5 contributions
